rzele, Oost-Vlaanderen, België","French Flanders, France":"Frans-Vlaanderen, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1000–":"about 1000–Deceased","1000–Female":"1000–Deceased","1000–Male":"1000–Deceased","1025–1071":"1025–1071","1051–1085":"1051–1085","–1070":"–1070","0980–Male":"0980–Deceased","1025":"1025","0980":"0980","about 1025":"about 1025","1000":"1000","before 1030":"before 1030","1085":"1085","1051":"1051","1071":"1071","about 1000":"about 1000","1070":"1070","Oosterzele, East Flanders, Belgium":"Oosterzele, East Flanders, Belgium","French Flanders, France":"French Flanders, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Earl","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>e(o)rl</i> ‘earl’, a traditional English title of nobility equivalent in rank to French and Norman   Count  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earle","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Harle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Johann, Kurt.","South German (<b>Härle</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>hār</i> ‘hair’.","English (northern) and Scottish: habitational name from Kirkharle and Little Harle in Northumberland (earlier simply <i>Herle</i>, <i>Harle</i>), possibly named from an Old English personal name <i>Herela</i> (a derivative of various compound names with the first element <i>here</i> ‘army’) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’."]},{"name":"Earls","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with genitival <i>-s</i>, denoting someone who was a member of an earl's household, or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In Ireland, when this is not the English name, it is from Gaelic <b>Mac an Iarla</b> ‘son of the earl’."]},{"name":"Hearl","meanings":["English: variant of   Earl   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Count","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."]},{"name":"Earll","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Earl  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Chester","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Chester, the county seat of Cheshire, or from any of various smaller places called with this word (as for example Little Chester in Derbyshire, Chester le Street in County Durham, or Chesters in Northumberland), which is from Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘Roman fort or walled city’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cheshire","meanings":["English: habitational name for someone from the county of Cheshire in northwestern England, the name of which is early recorded as <i>Cestrescire</i>, from the name of the county seat,   Chester  , + Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘district, division’."]},{"name":"Chesterman","meanings":["English: possibly a topographic name for someone who lived by a Roman fort, Old English <i>ceaster</i>, or a habitational name for someone from any of the places mentioned at   Chester  ."]}]},{"name":"Ada","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin; it was not in general use before the late 18th century. It may be a Latinate variant of the biblical name   Adah .  However, it has also been explained as a pet form of   Adele   and   Adelaide  , Germanic female names of which the first element is <i>adal</i> ‘noble’. It was borne by a 7th-century abbess of Saint-Julien-des-Prés at Le Mans."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ada Oosterzele Earl of Chester was born about 1000, in France as the daughter of Oosterzele Earl of Chester. She married Gerbod II de Saint-Omer de Saint-Bertin before 1030, in France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1000–":"umbes 1000–Surnud","1000–Female":"1000–Surnud","1000–Male":"1000–Surnud","1025–1071":"1025–1071","1051–1085":"1051–1085","–1070":"–1070","0980–Male":"0980–Surnud","1025":"1025","0980":"0980","about 1025":"umbes 1025","1000":"1000","before 1030":"enne 1030","1085":"1085","1051":"1051","1071":"1071","about 1000":"umbes 1000","1070":"1070","Oosterzele, East Flanders, Belgium":"Oosterzele, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","French Flanders, France":"Flandre française, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1000–":"noin 1000–Kuollut","1000–Female":"1000–Kuollut","1000–Male":"1000–Kuollut","1025–1071":"1025–1071","1051–1085":"1051–1085","–1070":"–1070","0980–Male":"0980–Kuollut","1025":"1025","0980":"0980","about 1025":"noin 1025","1000":"1000","before 1030":"ennen vuotta